notesStmt.note: Catalog entry in English and description of the manuscript in French in ink pasted onto last flyleaf recto; catalog entry in English, number 237, and bookplate for Le Ch. Ferrão de Castelbranco (inside front cover).
Inscription in ink: "histoire de Nadir Chah beau manuscrit qui m'a été donné par le Roi du Perse en 1806" [signature illegible] (front flyleaf verso)

msContents.summary: History of Nādir Shah, known as Jahān Gushā. Some half page spaces are left blank (see f. 34v for example).
msContents.textLang: Persian with a few phrases in Arabic

author.name: Free Library of Philadelphia. Rare Book Department. John Frederick Lewis Collection of Oriental Manuscripts

respStmt.persName: Ferrão de Castelo Branco, Jean de Carvalho Martins, 1805-1849

supportDesc.extent: i, 169, i leaves : 230 x 140 (170 x 92) mm, bound to 175 x 147 mm
supportDesc.foliation: Modern foliation added in pencil, upper left recto; catchwords every verso, lower left.

layoutDesc.layout: 19 long lines; ruled with a misṭarah.

scriptDesc.scriptNote: Written in nastaʻlīq shikastah in black ink; pointed; Arabic in naskh.

decoDesc.decoNote: Texblock border-ruled in red, gold, dark blue; rubrications in red; page-opening frame-ruled in gold.
Catalog entry and note in French

binding.p: Lacquered boards; plain black outside covers, red inside covers with painted central mandorla and two pendants on the vertical axis.

origin.p: Copy completed in Iṣfahān in 1178 A.H. (1764-1765 CE) (f. 169v).

history.provenance: Formerly owned by Le Ch. Ferrão de Castelbranco with the address 70 Avenue des Champs-Elysées; probably Jean de Carvalho Martins Ferrão de Castelo Branco (1805-1849) (bookplate inside front cover).
Sold at an Anderson Auctions in 1910 (note in pencil, front flyleaf verso).
Formerly owned by John Frederick Lewis (bookplate, back flyleaf verso).
